  <h2>Common Indoor Start Situations</h2>

  <div class="scenarioGrid">
    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Peppers Waiting on a Late Spring</h3>
      <p>
        Deep cell trays often make sense here because peppers usually stay indoors longer and lose quality faster in small cells.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Tomatoes With a Predictable Transplant Date</h3>
      <p>
        Standard trays may be enough if the outdoor window is consistent and the seedlings do not stay inside too long.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Brassicas for an Early Cool-Season Transplant</h3>
      <p>
        Deep cells can help, but they are often not necessary if the seedlings move out on schedule.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Mixed Home Seed Starting in a Short Season</h3>
      <p>
        Often best handled with a mix of tray sizes rather than forcing everything into either shallow or deep formats.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Do</h2>

  <p>
    Use deep cell trays for the crops and situations where standard cells regularly run out of time. That usually means slower crops, longer indoor starts, or gardens where spring transplanting often gets delayed.
  </p>

  <p>
    Do not feel like every seedling needs deep cells. For many home gardeners, the smartest system is a mix: standard trays for quick or flexible crops, and deep cells for the seedlings most likely to get crowded before the weather cooperates.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Deep cell trays are best when they solve a real timing problem, not just when they look like the premium option.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best deep cell trays are the ones that give longer indoor starts enough root room to stay healthy without forcing unnecessary bulk into the rest of your setup.
  </p>

  <p>
    They are most useful for slower crops, delayed transplant windows, and short-season gardens where seedlings often need more indoor margin. If your starts routinely outgrow standard trays before the garden is ready, deep cells are often worth it. If not, standard trays may still be the better fit.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Use deep trays where they buy time you actually need.
  </p>
</section>